# BETTER AS SEPARATE DOCS PAGES

These topics often make a README feel dense or intimidating. Prefer linked docs pages when the content is more than a short overview:

- **Detailed architecture**: component diagrams, dependency trees, request/data flow, and deployment topology.
- **Full command or API reference**: every CLI command, runtime parameter, environment variable, or interface field.
- **Comprehensive local development guide**: full repo tour, service-by-service dev workflows, and editor-specific setup.
- **Testing and debugging guide**: interactive test modes, log locations, debugging workflows, and common diagnostics.
- **Advanced configuration**: feature flags, compatibility modes, infrastructure customization, and runtime parameter design.
- **Feature-specific deep dives**: MCP, OAuth, A2A, auth providers, deployment variants, or platform-specific behavior.
- **Troubleshooting catalog**: long symptom-by-symptom matrices are better in docs than in the main README.

For the README itself, keep only the short version:

- one-paragraph architecture summary, if needed
- one quick-reference table for the most common commands or settings
- one short local-dev section
- a handful of common issues
- links to deeper docs for everything else

# PATTERNS TO MIRROR

| Pattern | Typical use |
| ------- | ----------- |
| Versioned prerequisite table | Quick scan for “do I have the right stack?” |
| Single primary install + alternatives | Reduces friction; experts use binaries or source |
| “Use this / Don’t use this” guidance | Helps readers decide quickly whether the repo fits |
| Minimal example before deep reference | Shows success path before detail |
| Short repo structure tree | Speeds orientation without turning the README into a repo tour |
| Wizard steps in a collapsible or linked doc | Keeps the main README readable |
| Port table | Essential for multi-service templates |
| Changelog + versioning link | Sets expectations for updates and compatibility |
| Example “outputs” block after deploy | Users know what URLs/IDs to copy |
| Symptom / solution troubleshooting | Faster resolution than narrative-only text |
| Link out long deep dives | Keeps the README approachable for new users |
